+---
+title: Execution patterns
+description: How queue-level execution patterns (static-dag, pipeline, map-reduce) layer above the engine tick — including the extendRun seam, run.extended audit events, the gate/respawn circle-back, and the merged-graph validation invariant.
+---
+
+The core engine described in [How an offload run executes](/pangolin/explanation/how-offload-runs/)
+is deliberately simple: a DAG of WorkItems, a dependency resolver, and a
+fire-and-reconcile tick loop. Execution patterns are a **strategy layer above that
+engine** — they inspect terminal items after each tick and may append new items to
+a live run. Nothing inside the engine changes; the pattern phase is a hook that runs
+between the engine tick and the seal check.
+
+This page explains what patterns are, how to attach one to a queue, the mechanics of
+the `extendRun` seam and the `run.extended` audit event, how the pipeline gate
+circle-back works, and why the merged-graph validation invariant is the guarantee
+that keeps dynamically-grown graphs acyclic and auditable.
+
+## What an execution pattern is
+
+A pattern is a **pure object** associated with a queue. It implements two methods:
+`plan(run)` is called once at submit time to expand or normalize the submitted run
+before validation; `onTaskDone(item, ctx)` is called for every terminal item of an
+unsealed run, every tick, and may return a `SpawnDirective` — a batch of new
+`WorkItem`s to be appended to the run — or `null`.
+
+Three built-in patterns ship with `pangolin-orchestrator`:
+
+- **`static-dag`** — the default no-op. `plan` is the identity; `onTaskDone` always
+  returns `null`. The run is exactly what was submitted. Use this (or omit
+  `pattern`) when the full graph is known at submit time.
+- **`pipeline`** — at submit time, `plan` synthesizes a linear chain by setting each
+  item's `depends_on` to the previous item's id (only for items that have empty
+  `depends_on`, except the first). At runtime, `onTaskDone` does nothing for a
+  green item; it only fires when a *gate item* — an item carrying a `GateConfig`
+  on its reserved `inputs.gate` key with `onRed: 'spawn-fix'` — is red (failed, or
+  done with `verify.passed === false`). When that happens it emits the
+  **gate/respawn lineage**: a fresh fix-and-retry sub-graph appended to the same
+  run.
+- **`map-reduce`** — a **splitter item** is any item whose reserved
+  `inputs.mapReduce` key carries a `MapReduceConfig`. After the splitter reaches
+  `done`, the pattern reads its `outputRefs` and emits one `map-<key>` WorkItem
+  per output key; once every map is `done`, it emits a single `reduce` item that
+  pulls each map's product into a `needs.<prefix>-<key>` binding. The number of
+  map items is unknown at submit time.
+
+Patterns are pure: they read item state, they never write it directly, and they keep
+no mutable variables between calls. Spawn ids are **deterministic** given the items
+that triggered them, which matters for crash-recovery (below).
+
+## Queue-level pattern config
+
+Patterns are configured **per queue** when constructing the orchestrator, not per
+run. This means every run placed on a queue with `pattern: pipeline` is governed by
+the pipeline pattern; you do not opt individual runs in or out.
+
+```ts
+import {
+  PangolinOrchestrator,
+  staticDag, pipeline, mapReduce,
+} from '@quarry-systems/pangolin-orchestrator';
+
+const orchestrator = new PangolinOrchestrator({
+  store, executors, triggers,
+  queues: {
+    default: { concurrency: 4 },                       // no pattern — static-dag behaviour
+    review:  { concurrency: 1, pattern: pipeline },
+    fanout:  { concurrency: 8, pattern: mapReduce },
+  },
+});
+```
+
+`queues` is a `Record<string, QueueConfig>` keyed by queue name, and each
+`QueueConfig` is `{ concurrency: number; pattern?: Pattern }`. The `pattern` value
+is a `Pattern` object — `{ id, plan, onTaskDone }` — not a configuration shape with
+a `type` discriminant. Pattern-specific knobs (the gate's `fixTemplate` and
+`maxFixAttempts`; the splitter's `map`/`reduce` `SpawnTemplate`s) live on individual
+items' reserved input keys (`inputs.gate`, `inputs.mapReduce`), not on the queue.
+
+Pattern config is validated at **submit time**, not at startup: the orchestrator
+constructor only registers queues with the store. When you call `submitRun`, the
+orchestrator runs `pattern.plan(run)` before normalization and validation, and
+`plan` is the chokepoint that surfaces a malformed pattern config (for example,
+`map-reduce.plan` calls `assertMapReduceConfig` on each splitter item it finds and
+throws a descriptive `Error` before `saveRun` touches the store).
+
+Submitting to a pattern-bound queue does not require any specific item to be
+present. `pipeline.plan` will chain whatever items the run carries, in submission
+order, with no requirement that any of them be a gate; `map-reduce.plan` accepts a
+run with zero splitters (and rejects only if more than one item carries
+`inputs.mapReduce`). The pattern only does work once an item with the right
+reserved-input key actually terminates.
+
+## The extendRun seam and run.extended audit events
+
+When a pattern returns spawns, the orchestrator applies them through the **`extendRun`
+seam** — the single code path through which any dynamic growth of a run is allowed.
+`extendRun` does the following before the tick resumes:
+
+1. **Skips ids already present.** Spawn batches are filtered against the run's
+   existing items (by namespaced id), so a pattern that re-emits the same
+   deterministic ids after a crash is a no-op rather than an error. The runaway
+   fuse rejects the batch if the post-extension total would exceed
+   `maxItemsPerRun`.
+2. **Validates the merged graph** — existing items plus the proposed spawns,
+   de-namespaced into the same logical-id space `validateRun` uses at submit time.
+   Cycles, missing `depends_on` targets, and schema violations reject the whole
+   spawn batch, not just the offending item, and leave the store unchanged.
+3. **Attributes** the spawn to the actor `pattern:<queueName>` (e.g.
+   `pattern:review`), so the audit trail distinguishes human submits from
+   machine-driven growth.
+4. **Records** a single `run.extended` audit entry per call — i.e. per spawn batch
+   — naming the **cause item**, the terminal item whose completion triggered the
+   spawn. The entry shape is `{ kind: 'run.extended', runId, itemId: <cause>,
+   actor, at }`; the spawned items' specs themselves are not carried inside the
+   audit entry. The audit append is best-effort and never aborts the spawn.
+
+Because `extendRun` runs **before the tick's seal check**, a run that just grew
+structurally cannot be sealed that tick. Sealing requires every item to be terminal;
+newly spawned items start as `pending`, so the run stays unsealed until the next
+tick's reconcile cycle catches up. This ordering is intentional: it prevents a
+pattern and the seal from racing.
+
+## The gate/respawn circle-back
+
+The pipeline pattern's most non-obvious behaviour is the **gate/respawn
+circle-back**: a mechanism that lets a failed gate trigger a fresh fix attempt on the
+*same run*, rather than failing the run outright.
+
+A pipeline gate is an ordinary WorkItem whose `inputs.gate` carries a `GateConfig`
+naming a `subject` (the upstream item whose product is being gated), an `onRed`
+policy, an optional `fixTemplate`, and an optional `maxFixAttempts` bound (default
+`1`). If the gate's executor exits non-zero, the engine marks it `failed` in the
+normal way — its `depends_on` dependents skip-cascade and the run heads toward
+settled. But before settlement, the pattern phase fires. The pipeline pattern sees
+a gate item that is `failed` or done-but-red (`status === 'done'` and
+`verify.passed === false`) with `onRed: 'spawn-fix'`, and calls `respawnLineage`,
+which emits a respawn batch of `[fixItem, gateCopy, ...skippedCopies]`:
+
+- The **fix item** has id `${base}-fix-${attempt}` (base/attempt parsed from the
+  failed gate's id — `review~2` is attempt 2) and `depends_on: [config.subject]`.
+  Because the subject is already `done`, the fix is the only spawned item that is
+  immediately `ready` after `extendRun` inserts it.
+- The **gate copy** has id `${base}~${attempt + 1}` and carries the original
+  gate's `depends_on` and `needs` remapped through a substitution map
+  `S = { subject → fixId, gate.id → gateCopyId, ...skippedDescendantId →
+  ${base}~${next} }`. Because the original gate's `depends_on` includes the
+  subject, the remap rewrites that edge to point at the new fix — so the gate
+  copy depends on the just-spawned (and still `pending`) fix, not on the original
+  failed gate.
+- **Skipped-descendant copies** mirror the items that skip-cascaded from the
+  failed gate, with edges remapped through the same `S` — so a former dependent
+  of the gate now depends on the gate copy, chaining the new lineage together.
+
+The original gate item and its skipped descendants are untouched: they stay
+`failed`/`skipped` in the history. The respawn aborts (returns `[]`) if no
+`fixTemplate` is configured, if any lineage member is `cancelled`, or if the parsed
+attempt exceeds `maxFixAttempts`.
+
+The circle-back is not literally a cycle in the graph. It is new nodes appended
+downstream of a failed terminal node, chained to each other and to the already-done
+subject. The original gate's failure is sealed history; the new attempt is a new
+lineage. The run graph remains a DAG throughout.
+
+## The merged-graph validation invariant
+
+Every spawn that any pattern is allowed to produce is validated as part of the
+combined graph, not in isolation:
+
+**`extendRun` calls `validateRun` on the merged set of existing items plus spawned
+items, in the same logical-id space the submit-time validator uses.**
+
+The spawn batch may reference items that already existed in the run (e.g. the fix
+item depends on the subject) *and* items that are spawned in the same batch (e.g.
+the gate copy depends on the just-spawned fix). What it may not introduce is a
+cycle, a dangling `depends_on`, a schema violation, or a missing `needs` source —
+the same conditions `validateRun` rejects at submit. The whole batch is rejected
+all-or-nothing, with no partial application.
+
+This invariant has three consequences:
+
+**The graph is acyclic by construction.** `validateRun` rejects cycles in the
+merged graph just as it does at submit. Intra-batch dependencies are allowed (and
+are used by the respawn lineage), but they may not close a loop with existing
+items or with each other.
+
+**Replay is safe.** Because patterns are pure and spawn ids are deterministic, a
+pattern called twice on the same terminal-item state produces the same spawn
+batch. `extendRun`'s id-skip filter drops items whose ids already exist in the
+store, so a crash between the pattern call and the `run.extended` audit write
+produces a no-op on restart. The orchestrator re-derives the spawn directive,
+finds all ids already present, and continues. No dedup table, no idempotency key
+— deterministic ids plus the id-skip filter provide it for free.
+
+**Provenance closure holds for dynamically grown runs.** The `pangolin verify`
+command checks that every input consumed by every item is traceable to an
+upstream item's output in the same run. Spawned items enter the run through
+`extendRun` the same way original items enter through `submitRun`; they carry the
+same `needs` fields and produce the same `resultRef` artifacts. The verifier sees
+no difference between a statically submitted item and a dynamically spawned one
+— closure is verified over the full item set, however it grew, with no special
+case for patterns.
+
+Together these three properties mean that a run governed by a pattern — however many
+times it circles back, however many map items the splitter produces — remains as
+auditable and verifiable as a fully static DAG submitted in one shot.
